SIMPLE: sojourn
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sojourn
<hw>So"journ</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sojourned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Sojourning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>sojornen</ets>, <ets>sojournen</ets>, OF. <ets>sojorner</ets>,
<ets>sejorner</ets>, F. <ets>s⟦eacute⟧journer</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>sub</ets> under, about + <ets>diurnus</ets> belonging to the day.
See <er>Journal</er>, <er>Diurnal</er>.]</ety> <def>To dwell for a time;
to dwell or live in a place as a temporary resident or as a stranger,
not considering the place as a permanent habitation; to delay; to
tarry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Abram went down into Egypt to <qex>sojourn</qex> there.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. xii. 30.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Home he goeth, he might not longer <qex>sojourn</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The soldiers first assembled at Newcastle, and there
<qex>sojourned</qex> three days.</q> <rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sojourn</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sojourn
<hw>So"journ</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>sujurn</ets>,
<ets>sujur</ets>, <ets>sejor</ets>, F. <ets>s⟦eacute⟧jour</ets>. See
<er>Sojourn</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <def>A temporary residence, as
that of a traveler in a foreign land.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though long detained⟦br⟧
In that obscure <qex>sojourn</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sojourner</ent>⟦br⟧
